english:
  title: Written at the Public Residence of Daepoong County
  author: Yu Seungdan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The traveling horse cannot pause for even a moment—
    bound by the king's command with its rigid schedule.
    At midnight I rise, head propped against the lamplight,
    all day long the dust clouds sting my weary eyes.

    Everywhere the common homes have crumbled to ruin,
    yet the temples alone pass by in excessive wealth.
    Though they say the accumulated decay has been swept away,
    what remains is still the endless building of pagodas and shrines.

    In every county I traverse, most houses are broken and fences torn through,
    yet here and there a towering great mansion stands—all of them dwellings of monks.
    How can one not feel a heaviness in the heart?
    This is what my poem touches upon.
  footnotes:
    - Yu Seungdan served as a traveling official or inspector sent on royal business, hence the rigid schedule and constant movement referenced in the opening lines.
    - The contrast between the decay of common people's homes and the flourishing of Buddhist temples reflects the author's critique of religious institutions' economic privilege during this period.
